(A)

(i)

Expressing the ratio as a function of the odds

\[ Pr(X = a)/Pr(X = b) = \frac{\binom{n}{a}p^a (1-p)^{n-a}}{\binom{n}{b}p^b (1-p)^{n-b}} = \frac{\binom{n}{a}}{\binom{n}{b}}p^{a-b}(1-p)^{a-b} \] \[ =\frac{\binom{n}{a}}{\binom{n}{b}}odd^{a-b} \]

(ii)

prob_ratio1 <- function(n, a, b, odds =1) {
  (choose(n,a)/choose(n,b)) * odds^(a-b)
}
prob_ratio2 <- function (n, a, b, odds =1) {
  p = odds/(odds + 1)
  dbinom(a, n, p)/dbinom(b, n, p)
}

(iii)

prob_ratio1(50, a =5, b=45)

prob_ratio1(50, a=5, b=45, odds =9)
## [1] 6.765496e-39

## [1] 1
prob_ratio2(50, a =5, b=45, odds =9)
## [1] 6.765496e-39

(B)

(i)

Expressing the mathematical expression for the ratio

ratio 1

\[ \frac{Pr(\widehat{p}_x = 0)}{Pr(\widehat{p}_y = 0)} \\ = \frac{Pr(x/n = 0)}{Pr(y/n = 0)} \\ = \frac{Pr(x = 0)}{Pr(y = 0)} \\ = \frac{\binom{n}{0}p^0(1-p)^(n-0)}{\binom{m}{0}p^0(1-p)^(m-0)} \\ = \frac{(1-p)^n}{(1-p)^m} \]

ratio ii

\[ \frac{Pr(\widehat{p}_x = 1)}{Pr(\widehat{p}_y = 1)} \\ = \frac{Pr(x/n = 1)}{Pr(y/n = 1)} \\ = \frac{Pr(x = n)}{Pr(y = n)} \\ = \frac{\binom{n}{n}p^n(1-p)^(n-n)}{\binom{m}{m}p^m(1-p)^(m-m)} \\ = \frac{p^n}{p^m} \]

(ii)

For Ratio 1 increases as m increases

For Ratio 2 increases as m increases

(C)

(i)

Expectation is

\[ E(\widehat{p}) = E(X/n) = (1/n)E(X) = (1/n)np = p \]

Standard deviation is

\[ SD(\widehat{p}) = \sqrt{Var(X/n)} = \sqrt{(1/n^2)Var(X)} = \sqrt{(1/n^2)np(1-p)} = \sqrt{p(1-p)/n} \]

(ii)

calcsd <- function (n, p) {
  sqrt(p*(1-p) /n )
}
